&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;std::logic_error&lt;/code&gt; is a C++ standard library exception indicating a violation of logical preconditions or invariants in the program. Unlike errors caused by external conditions (network, memory), a &lt;code&gt;std::logic_error&lt;/code&gt; means there is a bug in the code itself — the program received invalid arguments or is in an impossible state. The standard library throws derived types like &lt;code&gt;std::invalid_argument&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;std::out_of_range&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;std::domain_error&lt;/code&gt;, all of which inherit from &lt;code&gt;std::logic_error&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>